                type="document" xml:id="d303">
                <head>303. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On March 7, 1963, Presidentʼs Special Representative <persName corresp="#p_BCB1"
                        >Bowles</persName> wrote in a memorandum to President <persName
                        corresp="#p_KJF1">Kennedy</persName> that he was “deeply concerned” about
                    the situation in Vietnam and argued that “we should seek ways to widen our
                    present set of political choices in dealing with the area as a whole and with
                    Vietnam in particular. I believe that the time may be ripe, for instance, for a
                    discreet, noncommittal, and confidential approach to the <gloss
                        target="#t_USSR1">USSR</gloss> in which the potential dangers to both Moscow
                    and Washington that the Vietnam impasse contains may be underscored.” For text,
                    see <ref target="frus1961-63v03#pg_136">
                        <hi rend="italic">Foreign Relations</hi>, 1961–1963, volume III, pages
                        136</ref>–<ref target="frus1961-63v03#pg_140">140</ref>.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
